ng and inspirational movies of the Great Depression and World War II, the cynical, anti-establishment films of the 60s and 70s, and the sci-fi and fantasy blockbusters of today. Lindvall considers how the presentation of cinematic prayer varies across race, age, and gender, and places the use of prayer in film in historical context, shedding light on the religious currents at play during those time periods.God on the Big Screen demonstrates that the way prayer is presented in film during each historical period tells us a great deal about America’s broader relationship with religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aMotion picturesxReligious aspects. 0aPrayer in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aAimee Semple McPherson.  aAmerican cinema.  aAmerican dream.  aAmerican silent film.  aCecil B. DeMille.  aChristianity.  aCold War.  aD. W. Griffith.  aDeath of God movement.  aGreat Depression.  aMary Pickford.  aRoman Catholic Church.  aRonald Reagan.  aVatican II.  aVictorian films.  aVietnam War.  aWall Street crash.  aWorld War II.  aapocalypse.  ababy boom.  ablasphemy.  achurch history.  acivil religion.  acivil rights movement.  acomic prayer.  adying prayers.  aexemplary prayer.  afairy tale.  afantasy genre.  afilm noir.  ahorror films.  ahow to pray.  aintercessory prayer.  aironic prayer.  aliberation theology.  apiety in films.  apopular culture.  apostmodernism.  arace cinema.  arace.  areligion and film.  areligious films.  areligious photoplays.  areligious pretenders.  arevelatory prayer.  ascience fiction films.  asilent films.  asports.  atelevangelists.  atraditional prayer.  avindictive prayer.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978